European debt write-downs are inevitable
Berkeley — — "That was just the Greek crisis," "That was just the crisis of Greece and Ireland," people used to think that way, but now it's not possible anymore, because it's clearly a crisis of the eurozone.
To deal with it is both easier and more difficult than usually anticipated.
The economic logic of this crisis is quite simple.
Greece's fiscal situation is problematic.
The banking sector in Ireland has problems.
The private debt market in Portugal has problems.
Spain has problems in all of the above three areas.
Although the details differ, the conclusion is the same: these countries all have to undergo a painful process of spending cuts.
To offset the side effects of austerity policies, the usual approach is to combine domestic spending cuts with currency depreciation.
Devaluation enhances export competitiveness, which means using external demand to compensate for internal demand.
However, these countries are all eurozone countries, and they do not have independent currencies to devalue, so they can only use internal devaluation as a substitute for external devaluation.
They must cut wages, pensions, and other costs to increase export competitiveness and achieve the effect of expanding external demand.
In fact, these crisis countries have made considerable efforts to tighten their belts.
But there is one economic variable that has not changed along with the adjustments of other variables, which is the debt of both public and private sectors.
The nominal value of government accumulated debt has not changed, and bank debt — except for some debts owed to junior creditors — has also remained largely unchanged.
This simple fact puts the internal devaluation strategy into a self-contradictory situation: the more wages and other costs are cut, the heavier the relative burden of accumulated debt becomes.
The heavier the debt burden, the more public spending must be cut and taxes increased to meet the debt obligations of the government and its protectors (such as banks).
This in turn requires more internal devaluation, further increasing the debt burden, leading to a vicious cycle that drags the economy into a depression.
Therefore, for the internal devaluation strategy to work, it is necessary to find a way to reduce the nominal value of debt.
The government debt must be restructured.
Bank debt must be converted into equity, and banks should be liquidated when they are insolvent.
Home mortgage debt must also be written down.
It is understandable that policymakers are unwilling to take this path.
Contracts are sacred.
The government is worried about losing the trust of the financial market.
If creditors are mainly from abroad, especially foreign banks, write-offs will only burden other countries.
These concerns are not without reason, but one should not draw unreasonable conclusions from them.
The only options are internal depreciation or external depreciation.
The leaders of European countries must choose one of the two.
They unanimously ruled out the path of external depreciation.
But internal depreciation necessarily requires debt restructuring.
Denying this is both illogical and unreasonable.
Debt restructuring is simple and straightforward.
The government can issue a batch of bonds with face values discounted by a certain ratio from the current debt face value.
Bondholders can choose either to hold onto their bonds and redeem them at face value later with a lower interest rate, or accept discounted bonds with a lower face value but an earlier maturity date and a higher interest rate.
This is not some cutting-edge technology; people have done this before.
But to make it work, there are three prerequisites.
The first is to assure bondholders of the safety of the new bonds.
Someone needs to guarantee these bonds.
In the 1980s, when Latin America restructured its debt under the Brady Plan, the U.S. Treasury played the role of the "big guarantor."
Now, the International Monetary Fund and the German government can take on this responsibility.
Second, all countries must act in unison.
Otherwise, a country's restructuring will raise expectations for other countries, leading to contagion effects.
Finally, the balance sheets of banks that suffer losses from debt restructuring must be strengthened.
These banks need to undergo real stress tests, not the tokenistic ones done earlier this year.
If debt restructuring signals capital inadequacy, a comprehensive debt-to-equity conversion must be carried out on the relevant banks' assets.
If that is not enough, the government must step in to inject capital into the relevant banks.
This point also requires coordinated action by all countries.
Once the banks' balance sheets are stabilized, it may be possible to restructure mortgages, bank debt, and other private sector debt without destabilizing the entire financial system.
Now let's talk about the biggest challenge.
All of this requires resolute leadership.
The German leaders must acknowledge that the country's banks have a significant exposure to the debt of peripheral eurozone countries, and the situation is dire.
They must convince the backroom bosses and voters that guaranteeing public funds for debt restructuring and bank recapitalization is a necessary condition for an internal devaluation strategy; since Germany has urged other EU countries to adopt this strategy, it should bear the responsibility of guaranteeing it without hesitation.
In short, European leaders, especially German leaders, need to make the consequences seem even more severe — otherwise, big trouble is coming.
Because that's just how it is.
